# TITTLE: School Funding Effects Data Science Project

This project shows the relationship between federal/state funding in Tittle I schools and student test scores. This provides interesting and diverse 
visualizations so that educators and people can explore the data trends. It also uses statistical evidence to interpret the data and define the 
relationships between the two factors.

Quoting Nelson Mandela "Education is the most powerful weapon to change the world", my goal in creating this project to inform people on how make
better decisions that relate to funding. 

## PROJECT OVERVIEW: Datasets for Washington and Ohio (2019 - 2024) states are cleaned and merged using Pandas. Visual data charts such as scatterplots 
and bar graphs were used to clearly visualize the data. Statistical evidence is derived from the line of best fit in the scatterplot and Spearman's 
correlation. 

## TECHNOLOGIES USED: Data Analysis done using Python, Seaborn, Pandas, and matplotlib. Data from NERD$ Database - Edunomics Labs. 

## RESEARCH QUESTIONS
1. Do economically disadvantaged schools get more per pupil funding compared the economically advantaged schools?
2. How do the economically disadvantaged schools perfom on the SBA assement compared to the more advantages schools?
3. To what extent does increasing the per student funding for economically disadvantaged students help them improve their SBA scores?

## CONCLUSION: The analysis showed that average per - stuent funding was approximately $19,000 in both states. High - poverty schools recieved more 
funding than low - poverty ones. However, funding allocations were uneven across certain years, with some years allocating more than others. Nevertheless,
a clear direct relationship was observed, with high - poverty schools consistently recieving more funding. Overall, this information showed that higher per
student funding for economicaly disdvantaged students does imporve their SBA performance, although results may vary depending on how states allocate and
utillize their funding.

## USAGE: Open in GoogleCollab

## FUTURE IMPROVEMENTS: Expanding the data information to include other states.

